  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How does modern Greek language differ from ancient Greek?",
  "response": "Modern Greek differs from Ancient Greek in several significant ways, spanning phonology, grammar, vocabulary, and usage. Here are some key differences:\n\n1. **Phonology**: \n   - **Vowel System**: Ancient Greek had a more complex vowel system with long and short vowels, as well as diphthongs (combinations of vowels in a single syllable). Modern Greek has simplified these sounds and mostly has a smaller set of vowel sounds.\n   - **Consonants**: The pronunciation of certain consonant sounds has changed. For example, the ancient sound \"b\" (beta) has become \"v\" in modern times.\n\n2. **Grammar**:\n   - **Case System**: Ancient Greek had a more complex case system with five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, vocative). Modern Greek retains three cases (nominative, genitive, accusative) and does not utilize the dative case in the same way.\n   - **Articles and Nouns**: The definite article in Modern Greek is more extensively used and essential to sentence structure. In Ancient Greek, articles were less common and sometimes absent.\n   - **Verb Conjugation**: Modern Greek verbs are generally simpler than those in Ancient Greek, with fewer forms and a reduction in the use of moods and voices. For example, the future tense in Modern Greek is often formed in simpler ways compared to the variety of future formations in Ancient Greek.\n\n3. **Vocabulary**:\n   - **Lexical Changes**: Many words from Ancient Greek have fallen into disuse, while new words have come into use, particularly due to political, social, and technological changes. Words of foreign origin, especially from Turkish and Italian, are present in Modern Greek.\n   - **Semantic Shift**: Some words have retained their form but have changed meanings over time.\n\n4. **Syntax**:\n   - **Word Order**: Ancient Greek was more flexible in terms of word order due to its rich inflectional system, while Modern Greek has a more standardized subject-verb-object (SVO) order.\n\n5. **Orthography**:\n   - **Alphabet and Diacritics**: While Modern Greek uses the same Greek alphabet, it has simplified the use of diacritics, which were more prevalent in Ancient Greek texts to indicate tones and breathings.\n\n6. **Literary and Functional Use**: \n   - Ancient Greek is primarily known through classical texts in philosophy, drama, and history, while Modern Greek is used in everyday conversation and contemporary literature.\n\nOverall, while Modern Greek descends from Ancient Greek and preserves many of its features, the evolution over centuries has led to distinct differences that reflect changes in culture, society, and linguistic tendencies.",
